**Nyūkawa Shrine** (にゅうかわじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945}} located in Nyūkawa-chō (formerly {{ill|lt=Ōno District|Q31671|WD=Q31671}}{{ill|lt=Nyūkawa Village (Gifu Prefecture)|Q7071339|WD=Q7071339|lt=Nyūkawa Village}}), {{ill|lt=Takayama City|Q622594|WD=Q622594}}, {{ill|lt=Gifu Prefecture|Q131277|WD=Q131277}}.

The shrine’s name is derived from {{ill|lt=Nyūkawa Village (Gifu Prefecture)|Q7071339|WD=Q7071339|lt=Nyūkawa Village}} in {{ill|lt=Ōno District|Q31671|WD=Q31671}} and has no direct relation to {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287}}’s {{ill|lt=Niukawakami Shrine|Q246370|WD=Q246370}}, {{ill|lt=Niukawakami Shrine Upper Shrine|Q10877366|WD=Q10877366}}, or {{ill|lt=Niukawakami Shrine Lower Shrine|Q10877367|WD=Q10877367}}.

=== Overview ===
Originally, it was Yakama Shrine, enshrined in the Bokata district of Nyūkawa Village. During the shrine consolidation policy ({{ill|lt=Shinto shrine consolidation|Q11590700|WD=Q11590700}}) in the late Meiji period, several shrines within the village were merged, and it was renamed **Nyūkawa Shrine**.

The date of establishment is unknown. In the past, it was known as “Yasō no Mori” and “Hachimen Aragū-gū” {{Sfn|Tsuchida|1987|p=43}}.

In {{ill|lt=1868|Q7717|WD=Q7717}} (Meiji 1), it was renamed Yakama Shrine {{Sfn|Tsuchida|1987|p=43}}. In {{ill|lt=1871|Q7746|WD=Q7746}} (Meiji 4), it became a village shrine.

In {{ill|lt=1907|Q2048|WD=Q2048}} (Meiji 40), Kumano Shrine and Kifune Shrine were merged into it. At the same time, an application was submitted to Gifu Prefecture to change the name from Yakama Shrine to Nyūkawa Shrine, which was approved the following year {{Sfn|Nyūkawa Village History|2000|p=436}}. In {{ill|lt=1913|Q2080|WD=Q2080}} (Taishō 2), Kumano Shrine was merged. In {{ill|lt=1914|Q2083|WD=Q2083}} (Taishō 3), it was officially renamed **Nyūkawa Shrine** {{Sfn|Tsuchida|1987|p=44}}.

Thereafter, through the early Shōwa period, shrines within Nyūkawa Village (including Shinmei Shrine, Kumano Shrine, Suwa Shrine, and Bijoshima Shrine) were successively merged {{Sfn|Tsuchida|1987|p=44}}. As repeated mergers made the precincts cramped, the grounds were expanded and improved in {{ill|lt=1952|Q5272|WD=Q5272}} (Shōwa 27), and a new main hall and other buildings were constructed {{Sfn|Tsuchida|1987|p=44}}. In the same year, Hakusan Shrine was merged.

In {{ill|lt=1956|Q5221|WD=Q5221}} (Shōwa 31), it was designated a {{ill|lt=Kinpeisha|Q119929592|WD=Q119929592|lt=Ginpeisha}} by the Gifu Prefectural Association of Shinto Shrines {{Sfn|Tsuchida|1987|p=44}}.

